SIMPLE: copse
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Copse
<hw>Copse</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Contr. from
<ets>coppice</ets>.]</ety> <def>A wood of small growth; a thicket of
brushwood. See <er>Coppice</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Near yonder <qex>copse</qex> where once the garden smiled.</q>
<rj><qau>Goldsmith.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Copse</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Copse
<hw>Copse</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To trim or cut; --
said of small trees, brushwood, tufts of grass, etc.</def>
<rj><au>Halliwell.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To plant and preserve, as a copse.</def>
<rj><au>Swift.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Copsewood</ent>⟦br⟧
